Think of the game as starting from 0 and, on your turn, adding any whole number from 1 through 10 to the running total; whoever first brings the total to 50 wins.

1.  Work backward from 50.  
   • If the total is 40–49, the player to move can jump directly to 50 and win, so 40–49 are winning positions.  
   • Therefore 39 is a losing position (for the person who is about to play), because every legal move from 39 puts the opponent in the winning block 40–49.  

2.  Continue stepping back in blocks of 11 (because 1 + 10 = 11 is the largest amount two consecutive moves can change the total by).  
   39 is losing → 28 is losing → 17 is losing → 6 is losing → –5 would be next but is below 0, so we stop.

   Thus the “target” totals Gretchen wants to leave to Henry after each of her plays are  
        6, 17, 28, 39, 50.

3.  Strategy: whenever Henry says a number h, Gretchen answers with the unique number g that makes h + g = one of the targets above and also satisfies 1 ≤ g ≤ 10.  Concretely, she always adds the complement to 11:

        Gretchen’s reply = 11 − (amount Henry just added).

   This keeps the running total on the list 6 → 17 → 28 → 39 → 50.

4.  To get on that list immediately, Gretchen must open the game by saying 6.

   Then:
        Henry raises it to some number between 7 and 16;
        Gretchen replies to make 17;
        Henry raises it to 18–27;
        Gretchen replies to make 28;
        Henry raises it to 29–38;
        Gretchen replies to make 39;
        Henry is forced into 40–49;
        Gretchen ends the game at 50 and wins.

Therefore, by starting with 6 and thereafter always “completing 11,” Gretchen is guaranteed victory.

Final answer: 6
